<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Merlot's aging potential varies dramatically based on origin and winemaking style. <strong>Premium Bordeaux Right Bank Merlots</strong> from estates like Château Pétrus or Le Pin can evolve beautifully for 20-30 years, while high-quality Napa Valley Merlots typically peak between 10-15 years. Entry-level Merlots are best consumed within 2-3 years of vintage.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700">Evolution Timeline</h3>

<p>Young Merlots display vibrant <strong>primary fruit flavors</strong>—blackberry, plum, and cherry—supported by firm but approachable tannins. During the first 3-5 years, the wine's natural acidity helps preserve freshness while tannins begin softening through polymerization. <strong>Peak drinking windows</strong> occur when primary fruit transitions to complex secondary characteristics: leather, tobacco, dried herbs, and earthy minerality emerge around years 5-8 for quality expressions.</p>

<p>Well-aged Merlots develop <strong>tertiary complexity</strong>—forest floor, truffle, cedar, and dried fruit notes—while maintaining Merlot's signature velvety texture. The wine's color evolves from deep purple to garnet with brick-orange edges.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700">Proper Storage Conditions</h3>

<p>Store Merlot at <strong>55-58°F (13-14°C)</strong> with 70-75% humidity in a vibration-free environment. Bottles should lie horizontally to keep corks moist. Avoid temperature fluctuations exceeding 3-5 degrees, which can cause premature aging through cork expansion and contraction.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700">Aging Assessment</h3>

<p><strong>Properly aged Merlot</strong> shows clear, brilliant color with natural sediment, complex aromatics, and integrated tannins. <strong>Warning signs of spoilage</strong> include: cloudy appearance unrelated to sediment, vinegar-like acetic acid aromas, or complete fruit absence. Corked wines display musty, wet cardboard odors from TCA contamination. Premium Merlots with good provenance can surprise with their longevity—patience often rewards collectors with extraordinary complexity.</p>

