  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wines are similar to Merlot if I want to explore other varieties?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">If you enjoy Merlot's smooth, fruit-forward character, try Grenache from the Rhône Valley or Australia, which offers similar approachability with red fruit flavors and soft tannins. Carménère from Chile provides comparable richness with added herbal complexity, while Sangiovese from Tuscany offers medium body with bright acidity and cherry notes. For a step up in intensity while maintaining elegance, explore Cabernet Franc from the Loire Valley, which shares Merlot's silky texture but adds more pronounced herbaceous characteristics.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the best value region for quality Merlot under $25?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Washington State's Columbia Valley consistently produces exceptional Merlot values, with producers like Chateau Ste. Michelle and L'Ecole No. 41 offering complex, well-structured wines under $25. Chile's Colchagua and Maipo Valleys also provide outstanding value, particularly from producers like Santa Rita and Montes, which benefit from ideal growing conditions and modern winemaking techniques. These regions offer the varietal purity and quality that rivals much more expensive Bordeaux examples.</p>
